Prerequisites and objectives

The solutions assume the following packages and datasets are attached (other packages will be attached when needed):

# attach packages
library("sf")
library("raster")
library("RQGIS3")
library("vegan")
library("mlr")
library("parallelMap")
library("lattice")
library("latticeExtra")
library("grid")
library("dplyr")
library("vegan")

# attach data
data("dem", "study_area", "random_points", package = "RQGIS3")

The objective of this exercise is to spatially predict the floristic gradient along the southern slope of Mt. Mongn in northern Peru. For this you will have to perform following steps:

  1. Run a DCA and PCA, and decide which methods fits better the multi-dimensional input matrix in two dimensions.
  2. Compute environmental predictor rasters using R-GIS bridges.
  3. Model the ordination scores as a function of the obtained environmental predictors.
  4. Use the model coefficients to make a spatial prediction of the ordination scores, i.e., to visually represent the floristic gradient.
  5. Apply a spatial cross-validation to obtain a bias-reduced performance estimate.

To get a better understanding of the data we will use (plant species community matrix from the Lomas mountain Mt. Mongn in northern Peru), please refer to Chapter 14 of Geocomputation with R (Lovelace, Nowosad, and Muenchow 2019) and our RQGIS (Muenchow, Schratz, and Brenning 2017) and Predictive mapping papers (Muenchow et al. 2013).

1 Run an ordinationExported Items

Subject the presence-absence of data("comm", package = "RQGIS") to a PCA and DCA. How much of the total variance do the first axes of both methods explain? And do the biplots show convincingly strong gradients along the first and second axis?

Figure 1.1: Plotting the first two axes of a PCA (left panel) and a DCA (right panel).

Further recommended reading on ordinations:

  • The interpretation of ecological data (Pielou 1984)
  • Analyzing ecological data (Zuur, Ieno, and Smith 2007)
  • Statistical learning with R (unsupervised method chapters) (James et al. 2013)

2 Compute predictor raster stack

Compute an environmental predictor raster stack. At the least use elevation, slope and NDVI (data("ndvi", package = "RQGIS")) for the raster stack, and if time permits, add also catchment area, the SAGA wetness index and curvature variables (hint: check out grass7:r.slope.aspect, and also have a look at Chapter 9 of Geocomputation with R) (Lovelace, Nowosad, and Muenchow 2019). Additionally, reading the RQGIS paper might be helpful (Muenchow, Schratz, and Brenning 2017). Finally, construct a response-predictor matrix. The scores of the first ordination axis (which were the result when using the presence-absence community matrix) represent the response variable, and should be joined to random_points (use an inner join, and remember that the row.names of comm correspond to the id-column of random_points). To complete the response-predictor matrix, extract the values of the environmental predictor raster stack to random_points.

Here a quick glance at the first three raster layers of the environmental raster stack:

3 Model the ordination scores

Use a modeling/machine-learning algorithms (as long as it is not a random forest model) of your choice to model the ordination scores as a function of the obtained environmental predictors:

  • Briefly explore the data, i.e., plot the response variable against each predictor and check for collinearity among the predictors.
  • Dismiss strongly correlated predictors.
  • Subsequently, start easy, and simply try a linear model (lm). Later on, you can still test further algorithms such as a GAM, support vector machines, kmeans, gradient boosting, etc.
  • (Optional: Find the optimal hyperparameters (of course, using spatial cross-validation).)
  • Make a prediction map based on the fitted model.

A look at Chapters 11 and 14 of Geocomputation with R might be helpful.

Figure 3.1: Plotting the response against possible predictors.

Figure 3.2: Spatial prediction of ordination scores.

4 Spatial cross-validation (lm)

Retrieve the bias-reduced RMSE of a linear model using spatial cross-validation (5 folds and 100 repetitions, i.e., in total 500 models have to be fitted). Report the mean RMSE and use a boxplot to visualize all retrieved RMSEs. Reading Chapter 11 of Geocomputation with R will certainly be helpful.

Figure 4.1: RMSE boxplot of a spatially cross-validated linear model (500 runs).

5 Spatial cross-validation (random forest) (optional)

Retrieve the bias-reduced RMSE of a random forest model using spatial cross-validation including the estimation of optimal hyperparameter combinations (random search with 50 iterations) in an inner tuning loop. Parallelize the tuning level. Please note that this setup implies that R has to run 125,500 models, i.e., it might take a while. Report the mean RMSE and use a boxplot to visualize all retrieved RMSEs while comparing it with the RMSE values as obtained from the linear model. Reading Chapter 14 of Geocomputation with R will certainly be helpful.

Figure 5.1: Comparing the spatial CV results of a random forest (125,500 runs) and linear model (500 runs).

Further recommended reading on spatial cross-validation:

  • Random forest paper (Breiman 2001)
  • Spatial cross-validation paper (Brenning 2012)
  • Statistical learning with R (James et al. 2013)
  • Chapters 11 and 14 of Geocomputation with R (Lovelace, Nowosad, and Muenchow 2019)
  • Tuning random forest hyperparamters paper (Probst, Wright, and Boulesteix 2019)
  • Tuning hyperparameters in a spatial modeling setting (Schratz et al. 2019)
